    correct: 1,
    explanation: `The VSS/TSS ratio is a useful indicator of sludge composition: (1) Typical activated sludge: 0.7–0.8 (70–80% volatile). The volatile fraction represents the active biological mass (microorganisms) and biodegradable organic matter. (2) Low VSS/TSS (< 0.6): indicates inorganic accumulation — grit carryover from preliminary treatment, chemical precipitates (from phosphorus removal with alum or ferric chloride), or industrial inorganic discharges. (3) High VSS/TSS (> 0.85): indicates very fresh sludge with low inorganic content, or a system with very little chemical addition. (4) Trend monitoring: a declining VSS/TSS ratio over time indicates increasing inorganic accumulation, which reduces the active biomass fraction and may affect treatment performance.`,
