    correct: 1,
    explanation: `A calibration curve is fundamental to quantitative laboratory analysis: (1) Preparation — prepare a series of standards at known concentrations (e.g., 0, 1, 5, 10, 20, 50 mg/L) using certified reference materials. (2) Measurement — measure the instrument response (absorbance for spectrophotometry, peak area for chromatography, etc.) for each standard. (3) Plot — graph instrument response vs. concentration; the relationship should be linear within the working range. (4) Regression — calculate the best-fit line (y = mx + b) using linear regression. (5) Unknown samples — measure the instrument response for unknown samples and calculate concentration from the calibration equation. (6) Acceptance criteria — the calibration curve must meet acceptance criteria (R² > 0.999 for most methods) before sample results are reported. Calibration curves must be prepared with each analytical batch.`,
