    question: `What factors affect the performance of UV disinfection in wastewater treatment?`,
    options: ["Only UV dose affects performance", "UV transmittance (UVT) of the effluent, TSS concentration, UV lamp intensity and age, hydraulic contact time, and the UV dose (mJ/cm²) delivered to the target organisms; turbidity and TSS shield pathogens from UV radiation", "UV disinfection is not affected by water quality", "Only lamp age affects UV performance"],
    correct: 1,
    explanation: `UV disinfection effectiveness depends on multiple factors: (1) UV transmittance (UVT) — the fraction of UV light (254 nm) that passes through the water; higher UVT means more UV reaches the pathogens. Typical secondary effluent UVT: 55–75%; tertiary effluent: 65–85%. (2) TSS — suspended particles shield pathogens from UV radiation; TSS > 10–20 mg/L significantly reduces UV effectiveness. (3) UV dose — the product of UV intensity (mW/cm²) and exposure time (seconds); typical dose for secondary effluent: 40–80 mJ/cm². (4) Lamp intensity — decreases with age (typically 10–20% reduction over 8,000–12,000 hours); lamp aging factor must be applied in design. (5) Hydraulic contact time — affected by flow rate and channel geometry. (6) Lamp fouling — mineral scaling and biological fouling reduce UV output; lamps must be cleaned regularly.`,
