    options: ["Free chlorine and combined chlorine are equally effective", "Free chlorine (HOCl and OCl⁻) is more effective as a disinfectant than combined chlorine (chloramines formed by reaction with ammonia); however, chloramines are more stable (longer residual), less reactive with organics (lower DBP formation), and are used in some systems for distribution system residual", "Combined chlorine is more effective than free chlorine", "Chloramines are not formed in wastewater"],
    correct: 1,
    explanation: `Chlorine chemistry in wastewater: (1) Free chlorine — hypochlorous acid (HOCl) and hypochlorite ion (OCl⁻); HOCl is the more effective disinfectant (10–80× more effective than OCl⁻); distribution between HOCl and OCl⁻ depends on pH (pKa = 7.5). (2) Combined chlorine (chloramines) — formed by reaction of free chlorine with ammonia: NH₃ + HOCl → NH₂Cl (monochloramine) + H₂O; further reactions form dichloramine (NHCl₂) and trichloramine (NCl₃). (3) Breakpoint chlorination — adding chlorine beyond the breakpoint destroys chloramines and produces free chlorine; the breakpoint occurs at approximately Cl₂:NH₃-N = 7.6:1 by weight. In wastewater with significant ammonia, chlorine reacts with ammonia to form chloramines; the disinfection efficiency is lower but the residual is more stable. Chlorination of wastewater also produces disinfection byproducts (trihalomethanes, haloacetic acids).`,
