    correct: 1,
    explanation: `The C:N ratio is critical for biological nitrogen removal: (1) Nitrification — requires adequate oxygen (4.6 g O₂/g NH₃-N) and alkalinity (7.14 g CaCO₃/g NH₃-N); carbon is not consumed by nitrification (nitrifiers are autotrophs). (2) Denitrification — requires a carbon source (electron donor) to reduce nitrate to N₂; approximately 2.86 g BOD is consumed per g NO₃-N reduced. (3) C:N ratio — the BOD:TKN ratio of the influent determines carbon availability for denitrification. Typical domestic wastewater: BOD:TKN = 4–8:1. (4) Insufficient carbon (BOD:TKN < 3:1) — denitrification is carbon-limited; an external carbon source (methanol, ethanol, acetic acid) may be needed. (5) Excess carbon (BOD:TKN > 8:1) — denitrification is complete but excess BOD may appear in the effluent. (6) Industrial wastewater — may have very low C:N ratios (e.g., food processing, pharmaceutical) requiring external carbon supplementation.`,
