    correct: 1,
    explanation: `Foaming in activated sludge is a significant operational problem: (1) Filamentous foaming — Microthrix parvicella (dominant in cold weather, low F:M, high FOG) and Nocardia/Gordonia (dominant in warm weather, high SRT) produce hydrophobic cell surfaces that stabilize foam. Foam can accumulate to depths of 1 metre or more and overflow tanks. (2) Surfactant foaming — detergents and surfactants in the influent can cause transient foaming, especially during high flows. (3) Control strategies — chlorination of RAS (2–5 mg/L Cl₂ for 30 minutes) can reduce filamentous organisms but may also harm floc-forming bacteria; reducing SRT reduces Microthrix (which requires long SRT); selectors (anoxic or anaerobic contact zone before aeration) reduce filamentous growth by promoting floc-formers; improving FOG removal at source reduces substrate for Microthrix; water sprays can knock down foam temporarily. (4) Monitoring — microscopic examination identifies the causative organism and guides control strategy.`,
