    correct: 1,
    explanation: `State point analysis (SPA) is a powerful tool for secondary clarifier evaluation: (1) Solids flux — the rate of solids transport through the clarifier (kg/m²/h) has two components: (a) downward flux from gravity settling (a function of MLSS and settling velocity); (b) downward flux from bulk liquid withdrawal (RAS pumping). (2) Flux curve — a plot of gravity settling flux vs. MLSS concentration; the shape depends on the sludge's settling characteristics (SVI). (3) Operating line — a straight line from the origin with slope = (Q + Q_RAS) / A (where A = clarifier area); the intersection with the flux curve gives the underflow concentration. (4) State point — the intersection of the operating line with the vertical line at the aeration tank MLSS; if the state point is below the flux curve, the clarifier is not limiting; if above, the clarifier is overloaded. (5) Applications — determine maximum allowable MLSS for a given RAS rate; optimize RAS rate; evaluate clarifier performance during high flows.`,
