    explanation: `Chemical phosphorus removal with ferric chloride: (1) Reaction — Fe³⁺ + PO₄³⁻ → FePO₄↓ (ferric phosphate, insoluble). Also: Fe³⁺ + 3OH⁻ → Fe(OH)₃↓ (ferric hydroxide, which can adsorb phosphorus). (2) Molar ratio — theoretically 1 mole Fe per mole P; in practice, Fe:P molar ratio of 1.5–2.5:1 is needed due to: competing reactions with hydroxide and carbonate; not all iron reacts with phosphate; some phosphorus is in organic or particulate form. (3) pH effect — optimal pH for FePO₄ precipitation is 5–7; at higher pH, Fe(OH)₃ forms preferentially. (4) Addition points — pre-primary (reduces primary clarifier load), post-primary (before aeration), post-secondary (before tertiary filtration), or simultaneous precipitation (in the aeration tank). (5) Sludge production — ferric chloride addition increases sludge production (FePO₄ and Fe(OH)₃ precipitates); approximately 2.7 kg dry sludge per kg Fe added. (6) Effluent TP — can achieve < 0.3 mg/L with proper dosing and tertiary filtration.`,
