    correct: 1,
    explanation: `Chemical feed pump calibration is essential for accurate dosing: (1) Importance — inaccurate dosing can cause under-treatment (regulatory non-compliance) or over-treatment (chemical waste, potential adverse effects). (2) Procedure for diaphragm metering pumps — (a) Set the pump to the desired stroke length and frequency. (b) Place the suction tube in a graduated cylinder filled with water or the actual chemical. (c) Run the pump for a measured time period (typically 1–5 minutes). (d) Measure the volume drawn from the graduated cylinder. (e) Calculate actual flow rate: Q (mL/min) = volume (mL) / time (min). (f) Compare to the set point; adjust stroke length or frequency if needed. (g) Repeat until the actual output matches the set point. (3) Frequency — calibrate monthly or quarterly, and after any pump maintenance or chemical change. (4) Documentation — record calibration results in the operating log.`,
