    correct: 1,
    explanation: `VFDs (also called variable speed drives or adjustable frequency drives) are widely used in wastewater treatment: (1) Operating principle — converts AC power to DC, then back to AC at a variable frequency (0–60 Hz); motor speed is proportional to frequency. (2) Energy savings — for centrifugal pumps and blowers, power varies with the cube of speed: P ∝ N³. Reducing speed by 20% reduces power by 49% (0.8³ = 0.51). (3) Applications — aeration blowers (match air supply to oxygen demand), influent pumps (match flow to wet well level), RAS pumps (adjust RAS rate), chemical feed pumps (adjust dosing rate). (4) Benefits — energy savings (20–50% for variable flow applications), reduced mechanical stress (soft starting eliminates inrush current and torque spikes), extended equipment life, precise flow control. (5) Limitations — VFDs generate harmonics that can interfere with other electrical equipment; heat generation requires adequate ventilation; not suitable for all motor types (must be inverter-duty rated motors for VFD applications).`,
