    correct: 1,
    explanation: `Reduced pump flow is a common operational problem requiring systematic troubleshooting: (1) Check system head — measure discharge pressure; high pressure indicates increased system resistance (partially closed valve, fouled pipe, check valve stuck partially closed, increased static head due to high wet well level). (2) Check for cavitation — listen for crackling/grinding noise; check NPSHa vs. NPSHr; ensure wet well level is above minimum. (3) Check impeller — worn impellers (from abrasive sludge or cavitation) reduce pump head and flow; check pump curve performance against design. (4) Check rotation — incorrect rotation (e.g., after motor rewiring) significantly reduces pump output; check rotation direction against the arrow on the pump casing. (5) Check suction — blockage in the suction line (rags, debris) or air leak in the suction pipe reduces flow. (6) Check pump curve — if the system head has increased, the operating point moves left on the pump curve to a lower flow; the pump may need to be replaced with one better suited to the new operating conditions.`,
