    correct: 1,
    explanation: `UV disinfection system maintenance is critical for reliable performance: (1) Lamp replacement — UV lamps lose intensity over time (10–20% reduction over 8,000–12,000 hours); lamps must be replaced before intensity drops below the minimum required for the design UV dose. Lamp replacement frequency depends on operating hours and the lamp aging factor used in design. (2) Lamp cleaning — mineral scaling (calcium carbonate, iron) and biological fouling reduce UV transmittance through the quartz sleeve; cleaning methods include: mechanical wipers (continuous or periodic), chemical cleaning (citric acid or sodium hypochlorite), or manual cleaning during maintenance. (3) UV intensity monitoring — UV sensors measure the UV intensity delivered to the water; sensor calibration must be verified regularly against a reference sensor. (4) Sleeve inspection — quartz sleeves can crack or become permanently fouled; inspect and replace as needed. (5) Ballast inspection — electronic ballasts control lamp power; check for overheating and proper operation. (6) Log reduction verification — periodic bioassay testing (using MS2 bacteriophage or Bacillus subtilis spores) verifies that the system is achieving the required log reduction.`,
