    correct: 1,
    explanation: `pH meter calibration is a routine laboratory and field procedure: (1) Frequency — calibrate before each use or at minimum daily for process monitoring; more frequent calibration for critical measurements. (2) Buffers — use NIST-traceable buffers at pH 4.00, 7.00, and 10.00; buffers expire and must be replaced regularly (typically 1–3 months after opening). (3) Two-point calibration — calibrate at two pH values that bracket the expected sample pH; the first point sets the offset (standardize at pH 7), the second point sets the slope (calibrate at pH 4 or 10). (4) Temperature — pH is temperature-dependent; modern meters have automatic temperature compensation (ATC) using a temperature probe; calibration and measurement should be at the same temperature, or ATC must be enabled. (5) Electrode care — rinse with deionized water between measurements; store in pH 4 buffer or KCl storage solution (not deionized water); replace the electrode when response time is slow or calibration is unstable. (6) Documentation — record calibration date, buffer values, meter readings, and any adjustments.`,
