    module: "Equipment Evaluation & Maintenance",
    question: `How do you evaluate whether a centrifugal pump is performing within its design specifications?`,
    options: ["Compare the pump's age to its expected lifespan", "Compare the measured operating point (flow and head) to the pump's performance curve; measure flow using a flow meter and head using pressure gauges on suction and discharge; if the operating point has shifted from the design point, investigate causes (worn impeller, changed system head, cavitation)", "Evaluate pump performance by listening for noise only", "Pump performance can only be evaluated during annual maintenance"],
    correct: 1,
    explanation: `Pump performance evaluation involves comparing actual operation to the design pump curve: (1) Measure flow — use an installed flow meter or portable ultrasonic meter. (2) Measure total dynamic head (TDH) — TDH = discharge head - suction head; use pressure gauges on suction and discharge flanges, converting to metres of head: h (m) = P (kPa) / (ρg) = P (kPa) / 9.81. (3) Plot the operating point — plot the measured flow and TDH on the pump curve; the operating point should be near the design point. (4) Interpret deviations — operating point shifted right (higher flow, lower head): system resistance has decreased (valve opened, pipe cleaned); shifted left (lower flow, higher head): system resistance has increased (fouled pipe, partially closed valve, increased static head); below the curve: worn impeller, air entrainment, or cavitation. (5) Efficiency — calculate pump efficiency: η = (ρgQH) / (motor power × motor efficiency); compare to design efficiency. (6) Trending — track pump performance over time to detect gradual deterioration.`,
