    module: "Equipment Evaluation & Maintenance",
    question: `How do you evaluate the performance of a secondary clarifier?`,
    options: ["Evaluate the clarifier by its age", "Key performance indicators: effluent TSS (< 10–20 mg/L), sludge blanket depth (< 1/3 of side water depth), surface overflow rate (< 16–24 m³/m²/day), solids loading rate (< 5–6 kg/m²/h), RAS concentration, and settleability tests (SVI, zone settling rate); visual inspection for scum, short-circuiting, and density currents", "Evaluate the clarifier by measuring the effluent pH only", "Clarifier performance can only be evaluated during shutdown"],
    correct: 1,
    explanation: `Secondary clarifier evaluation involves multiple performance indicators: (1) Effluent quality — effluent TSS is the primary performance indicator; consistently > 20–30 mg/L indicates a problem. (2) Sludge blanket depth — measure using a sludge judge or Imhoff cone; blanket should be < 1/3 of side water depth (SWD); rising blanket indicates overloading or poor settling. (3) Surface overflow rate (SOR) — SOR = influent flow / clarifier area; design limit typically 16–24 m³/m²/day (peak hour); exceeding the limit causes sludge carryover. (4) Solids loading rate (SLR) — SLR = (influent flow + RAS flow) × MLSS / clarifier area; design limit typically 5–6 kg/m²/h. (5) RAS concentration — should be 6,000–12,000 mg/L for typical activated sludge; low RAS concentration indicates poor settling (high SVI). (6) Settleability — SVI, zone settling rate (ZSR), and diluted SVI provide information about sludge settling characteristics. (7) Visual inspection — look for scum accumulation, short-circuiting (density currents visible as surface turbulence), and effluent weir uniformity.`,
