    correct: 1,
    explanation: `A CMMS (also called EAMS — enterprise asset management system) is a critical tool for modern wastewater treatment operations: (1) Work order management — create, assign, track, and close work orders for corrective and preventive maintenance; documents what was done, by whom, and when. (2) Preventive maintenance scheduling — automatically generates work orders based on time intervals or equipment runtime; ensures PM tasks are not missed. (3) Equipment history — maintains a complete record of all maintenance performed on each asset; used to identify chronic problems and justify replacement decisions. (4) Spare parts inventory — tracks spare parts inventory, generates purchase orders when stock falls below minimum levels, and links parts to equipment. (5) Maintenance cost tracking — tracks labour and material costs by asset, department, and work type; used for budget planning and cost-benefit analysis. (6) Asset management — CMMS data (maintenance history, costs, failure frequency) feeds into the asset management plan to support replacement decisions. (7) Regulatory compliance — maintenance records may be required by the ECA or during regulatory inspections.`,
