    options: ["Corrosion is only caused by high pH", "Primary causes: (1) hydrogen sulphide (H₂S) — oxidized to sulphuric acid (H₂SO₄) by Thiobacillus bacteria on moist concrete surfaces, causing microbially induced corrosion (MIC); (2) electrochemical corrosion — galvanic corrosion between dissimilar metals; (3) stray current corrosion; (4) carbonation of concrete; (5) chloride attack on reinforced concrete", "Corrosion is only caused by high flow velocity", "Corrosion is not a concern in modern wastewater systems"],
    correct: 1,
    explanation: `Corrosion is a major maintenance challenge in wastewater systems: (1) Microbially induced corrosion (MIC) — H₂S produced in anaerobic conditions (septic sewage, wet wells, force mains) is released into the gas phase above the waterline; Thiobacillus bacteria oxidize H₂S to H₂SO₄ on moist concrete surfaces; H₂SO₄ attacks the calcium silicate in concrete, forming gypsum (CaSO₄), which is soft and easily eroded; MIC can destroy concrete pipe at rates of 1–10 mm/year. (2) Prevention — H₂S control in the collection system (iron salts, oxygen injection, pH elevation); protective coatings on concrete (epoxy, polyurea); corrosion-resistant materials (HDPE, FRP, stainless steel). (3) Galvanic corrosion — occurs between dissimilar metals in contact in an electrolyte; the more active metal (anode) corrodes; prevent with dielectric unions, cathodic protection, or using compatible materials. (4) Stray current corrosion — caused by DC current from transit systems or cathodic protection systems; detected by potential measurements. (5) Chloride attack — chlorides penetrate concrete and depassivate the reinforcing steel, causing corrosion and spalling.`,
