    correct: 1,
    explanation: `Insulation resistance (IR) testing is a key predictive maintenance tool for electrical motors: (1) Principle — a megohmmeter (megger) applies a high DC voltage (typically 500V for motors rated < 1000V, 1000V for higher voltage motors) between the motor windings and ground; the resistance of the insulation is measured in megohms (MΩ). (2) Interpretation — IEEE 43 provides guidance: minimum acceptable IR = rated voltage (kV) + 1 MΩ (e.g., 480V motor: minimum 1.48 MΩ); good insulation: > 100 MΩ; IR < 1 MΩ indicates serious insulation degradation. (3) Causes of low IR — moisture ingress (condensation, flooding), contamination (oil, dirt, chemicals), insulation aging (thermal degradation, mechanical damage), winding shorts. (4) Trending — track IR over time; a declining trend indicates developing insulation problems before failure occurs. (5) Precautions — disconnect the motor from the VFD before megger testing (VFDs can be damaged by the high test voltage); discharge the windings after testing. (6) Frequency — test annually or after any motor repair or rewinding.`,
